text: 2024 marks the 10th year of release of the INFORM Risk Index. In 2014,
label: BODY

text: INFORM Partners first came together to create an open index for measuring
label: BODY

text: the risk of humanitarian crises globally. Since then, the INFORM Risk Index
label: BODY

text: and other INFORM products have become established and relied upon in
label: BODY

text: the decision-making systems of organisations across the multilateral system.
label: BODY

text: INFORM partners believe that the availability of shared analysis of crises
label: BODY

text: and disasters can lead to better coordination of actors and better outcomes
label: BODY

text: for at-risk and affected people. Specifically, INFORM creates a space and
label: BODY

text: process for shared analysis that can support joint strategy development,
label: BODY

text: planning and action to prevent, prepare for, respond to and recover from
label: BODY

text: crises. This can bring together development, humanitarian and other actors
label: BODY

text: to manage risk and respond better when crises do occur.
label: BODY

text: This report looks back on how INFORM has developed over that last decade
label: BODY

text: and analyses some trends in crises and crisis risk over that time. It sets out
label: BODY

text: INFORM’s vision for a suite of products to support decision-making that are
label: BODY

text: easy to use and open to everyone. This vision involves bringing scientific
label: BODY

text: rigour to the process of analysing crises and pooling expertise to develop
label: BODY

text: shared methodologies. By working together, we can reduce the investments
label: BODY

text: required by individual organisations, assure the quality of our analysis and
label: BODY

text: make it available for the common good.
label: BODY

text: In a world increasingly marred by complex crises, the mix of conflict, climate issues and economic
label: BODY

text: instability has exacerbated the reliance on humanitarian aid. Millions of people are displaced for long
label: BODY

text: periods and food insecurity is rising. Humanitarian responses, despite heroic efforts to scale up,
label: BODY

text: are struggling to meet people's needs, leaving more and more individuals without essential services
label: BODY

text: The European Union, grounded in the principle of solidarity, stands as the leading provider of
label: BODY

text: humanitarian and development aid in the world by far. In the face of escalating crises, the EU’s
label: BODY

text: commitment to providing humanitarian assistance remains firm. At the same time fostering
label: BODY

text: development investment to address root causes of humanitarian crises is crucial for steering affected
label: BODY

text: populations towards recovery and sustainable growth. And to do this correctly, we need scientific
label: BODY

text: This is why, the INFORM Partners, including the European Commission and humanitarian and
label: BODY

text: development organisations worldwide, joined forces ten years ago and created an open index for
label: BODY

text: measuring the risk of humanitarian crises. Since then, the INFORM Risk Index and other INFORM
label: BODY

text: products have become a key component of the decision-making systems of many organisations at
label: BODY

text: global as well as local levels.
label: BODY

text: The uniqueness of INFORM lies in its ability to enrich existing knowledge and improve common
label: BODY

text: understanding of disaster risks, the severity of the humanitarian crises and the impacts of climate
label: BODY

text: change. Through collective effort, it delivers scientifically sound, independent and objective analyses,
label: BODY

text: ensuring transparency and accountability in the political context of humanitarian aid. This facilitates
label: BODY

text: evidence-based allocation of humanitarian aid and at the same time enables integrated strategies for
label: BODY

text: The Commission, through its Joint Research Centre and the Department of Civil Protection and
label: BODY

text: Humanitarian Aid Operations, exemplifies the effectiveness of integrating evidence-based knowledge
label: BODY

text: into humanitarian actions. This alignment underscores the key role of science in bridging the
label: BODY

text: humanitarian gap and transforming crisis management trends.
label: BODY

text: As we mark the 10th year anniversary of the INFORM Risk Index, the first analytical tool within the
label: BODY

text: INFORM suite, we are reminded of the critical role of evidence-based collective action and the power
label: BODY

text: of solidarity in addressing the challenges we face.
label: BODY

text: Looking ahead, let us leverage the scientific insights provided by INFORM to guide our humanitarian
label: BODY

text: and development efforts, striving for a more resilient and sustainable future for all.
label: BODY

text: Together, we can make a difference and ensure that no one is left behind in times of crisis.
label: BODY

text: Over the last ten years (INFORM Risk Index 2015-2024), there has been a general increase in the risk of humanitarian crises
label: BODY

text: at global level. While there has been an improvement in coping capacity, this has been negated by large increases in the
label: BODY

text: number of people exposed to hazards, and to their vulnerability. The development of institutions and infrastructure has
label: BODY

text: helped decrease risks, but this has not kept pace with the increased exposure to natural hazards and conflict, combined
label: BODY

text: During the last decade, conflict, displacement and shocks like the Covid-19 crisis were important drivers of increasing
label: BODY

text: crisis risk. There is a noticeable increase in vulnerability and risk after 2020 that coincides with the timing of the Covid-19
label: BODY

text: pandemic and its effects. According to Global Humanitarian Overview 2023, the effects of the pandemic have triggered food
label: BODY

text: and energy price increases in crisis-affected countries. The effect of such price increases on vulnerable people could be
label: BODY

text: one mechanism through which the structural impacts of the pandemic continue to increase broader crisis risks.
